# Drugs for schizophrenia (51)  
[[Drugsandbrain:Lecture Week5Lecture51 | Lecture 51 Edited Text]]  
**Therapeutic approaches**  
* All present approved drugs for schizophrenia are antipsychotics.  
* They suppress the positive symptoms (psychoses, hallucinations, delusions), but do not suppress the negative symptoms nor the cognitive deficits.  
* All conceptual views of antipsychotic drugs assume that they act via “Outside-In” pathways (G protein-coupled receptors, G-protein intracellular messengers, their blockade or their activation).  
* There is no satisfactory explanation for the “therapeutic lag” (the two to three week time course between the the time a person starts taking a antipsychotic drug and the time it reaches its full effects)    
  
**Clinical potency of “classical” or “typical” antipsychotic drugs correlates best with
dopamine D2 receptor blocking dose**  
* upper left: this graph shows the correlation between their drug potency measured in cell-free systems or in cellular systems and the average clinical daily dose that is required to stabilize a patient.  
* There is good correlation for the antipsychotic drugs and the dopamine D2 receptor.  
* For the first generation drugs, the correlation is a lot poorer for the Serotonin 5HT2A/2C receptors. And there's a very poor correlation for the &alpha:1 adrenergic receptor and the histamine receptors, these are all GPCRs.   
    
**Not known how blocking Gi-coupled receptors reduces psychoses**  
* We’ve discussed these three effects of Gi-coupled receptors (mL 18, 19, 20, 21)  
* G protein-activated K channels  
* Decreased cAMP  
* Gene activation  
  
**Modern “atypical” antipsychotics also block other GPCRs and have fewer side effects**  
* Not known how blocking Gi or Gq-coupled receptors reduces psychoses  
* Some drugs bind most tightly to D1 dopaminergic receptors which are Gs-coupled, some to the 5HT2A receptor Gq coupled, and some to the original dopamine D2 and D3 receptor.  
* Each of these drug classes has side effects.  
:*  conventional pyschotic drugs: tardive dyskinesia - a movement disorder thought to be localized in the pathway from the midbrain to the striatum  
:* weight gain  
:* agranulocytosis (a decrease in white cells)
  
**Nicotinic drugs for cognitive enhancement in schizophrenia?**  
* ~90% of schizophrenics smoke.  
* Schizophrenics smoke more than typical nicotine addicts.  
* Schizophrenics take deeper breaths, hold the breath longer, and generally seem to extract much more nicotine per cigarette.  
* This practice may lead to activation of low-sensitivity nicotinic receptors.  
  
**The sensory gating anomaly (mL 50) maps near the α7 nicotinic acetylcholine receptor;
α7 agonists are being tested for cognitive enhancement in schizophrenia**  
  
